  {
    slug: '1996-berkshire-letter',
    year: 1996,
    type: 'berkshire',
    title: 'The Circle of Competence — 1996',
    date: '1997-03-00',
    summary:
      'Buffett formalized the "Circle of Competence" concept and discussed Berkshire\'s investment in a variety of businesses. He also explained the challenges of capital allocation as Berkshire grew larger and the search for "elephant-sized" acquisitions.',
    fullText: `<p><em>To the Shareholders of Berkshire Hathaway Inc.</em></p>

<p>Our gain in net worth during 1996 was $6.2 billion, or 36.1%. Per-share book value, however, grew by less, 31.8%, because the number of Berkshire shares increased. Over the last 32 years (that is, since present management took over) per-share book value has grown from $19 to $19,011, or at a rate of 23.8% compounded annually.</p>

<h2>The Circle of Competence</h2>

<p><strong>What an investor needs is the ability to correctly evaluate selected businesses.</strong> Note that word "selected": You don't have to be an expert on every company, or even many. You only have to be able to evaluate companies within your circle of competence. The size of that circle is not very important; knowing its boundaries, however, is vital.</p>

<p>For example, I have no competence in evaluating pharmaceutical companies, optical electronics companies, or coal companies. Within the pharmaceutical industry, I couldn't have told you which of the 300 companies in the field had the best chance to prosper. But I could have told you in 20 seconds — and with a high degree of conviction — that Procter & Gamble was a better business than any of them. To be a successful investor you must firmlygrid deals that are outside your circle of competence. That sounds easy, but it is not.</p>

<p><strong>If you aren't willing to own a stock for ten years, don't even think about owning it for ten minutes.</strong></p>

<h2>GEICO — The Crown Jewel</h2>

<p>GEICO now is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Berkshire Hathaway. On January 2, 1996 we completed our purchase of the 48% of GEICO shares that we didn't already own, paying $1.8 billion for them. This is the largest single acquisition Berkshire has ever made — and it came with a world-class management team led by Tony Nicely.</p>

<p>GEICO's competitive advantage is its ultra-low cost operation, which allows it to write coverage for risks that its higher-cost competitors cannot profitably touch. In 1996, GEICO's voluntary auto policy count grew 10%, far exceeding previous records. The company now writes over 1 million referral customers annually.</p>

<h2>Insurance — The Float Machine</h2>

<p>Our insurance float — funds we hold that will eventually be paid out to policyholders — grew to $6.702 billion at yearend 1996. Since 1967, when we entered the insurance business, this float has grown at a compounded rate of 22.3% annually. Even more important, the cost of this float has been less than nothing: we've actually earned money on the funds we hold.</p>

<p>This "negative cost of float" means that our insurance operations are not merely break-even; they are actively adding to our earnings. That's the magic of a business that collects premiums before paying losses — when managed by people who understand the business.</p>

<h2>Acquisitions — FlightSafety and Kansas Bankers Surety</h2>

<p>We made two acquisitions in 1996. FlightSafety International, the world leader in pilot training, was acquired for approximately $1.5 billion. FlightSafety operates 175 flight simulators at 41 locations worldwide. We were fortunate to acquire the company along with its founder, Al Ueltschi, who continues as CEO.</p>

<p>Kansas Bankers Surety, a specialty insurance company serving bankers, was acquired for $75 million and placed with Wesco under the management of Don Towle.</p>

<h2>The USAir Lesson</h2>

<p>Our investment in USAir continues to disappoint. We invested $358 million in 1989 and have written it down to $89.5 million. The airline industry has proven to be an extraordinarily difficult business — one where the competitive dynamics almost guarantee that most participants will destroy themselves through capital-intensive competition. <strong>This has been a costly lesson about the dangers of commodity-type businesses with high fixed costs.</strong></p>

<h2>On Intrinsic Value</h2>

<p>Our measure of intrinsic value remains an estimate, but it is the figure that Charlie Munger and I use to evaluate Berkshire. We believe it is far more important to focus on business value than on accounting earnings. Accounting numbers are the creation of accountants; business value is what the business is actually worth.</p>

<p><em>Warren E. Buffett, Chairman<br/>February 28, 1997</em></p>`,
