  {
    slug: '1978-berkshire-letter',
    year: 1978,
    type: 'berkshire',
    title: 'Steady Progress — 1978',
    date: '1978-02-01',
    summary:
      "1978 was a year of solid progress. GEICO's turnaround continued to contribute to earnings while investment portfolio performed well.",
    fullText: `<p><strong>Warren E. Buffett</strong><br/>March 14, 1979</p>
<p>To the Stockholders of Berkshire Hathaway Inc.:</p>
<p>Operating earnings in 1978 improved to $32.5 million from $25.1 million in 1977, and return on beginning equity capital (with securities valued at cost) increased to 19.4% from 19.0%. We consider this return to be a reasonably accurate measure of economic performance in a single year.</p>
<h2>Textile Operations</h2>
<p>The textile industry continued to struggle in 1978. We experienced poor results throughout the year, with the fourth quarter particularly disappointing. The industry is plagued by excess capacity and rising costs, particularly in energy. We have continued to invest in modernization, but the returns remain inadequate.</p>
<h2>Insurance Operations</h2>
<p>Our insurance operations had an excellent year. National Indemnity Company, under the leadership of Phil Liesche, continued to produce outstanding underwriting results. GEICO, under Jack Byrne, made dramatic progress in its turnaround. Underwriting losses were reduced substantially, and we are optimistic about future prospects.</p>
<h2>Banking Operations</h2>
<p>Illinois National Bank continued its excellent performance, earning over 2% after tax on average deposits. Gene Abegg and Bob Kline have done an outstanding job in managing this operation.</p>
<h2>Investments</h2>
<p>Our equity investments performed well in 1978. We continued to concentrate our holdings in a few companies that meet our investment criteria. We are not concerned with short-term market fluctuations; our focus is on the long-term business performance of the companies we own.</p>
<p><em>Warren E. Buffett, Chairman</em></p>`,
    concepts: ['intrinsic-value', 'moat', 'compounding', 'owner-earnings'],
    companies: ['berkshire-hathaway'],
    people: ['charlie-munger'],
    crossReferences: [],
    keyQuotes: [],
    featured: false,
    sourceUrl: 'https://www.berkshirehathaway.com/letters/1978.html',
    readingTimeMinutes: 8,
  },
  {
    slug: '1979-berkshire-letter',
    year: 1979,
    type: 'berkshire',
    title: 'Diversified Strength — 1979',
    date: '1979-02-01',
    summary:
      "1979 showed mixed results. Textile operations faced challenges while insurance and investments provided steady contributions.",
    fullText: `<p><strong>Warren E. Buffett</strong><br/>March 15, 1980</p>
<p>To the Stockholders of Berkshire Hathaway Inc.:</p>
<p>Operating earnings in 1979 improved to $36.0 million from $32.5 million in 1978, but return on beginning equity capital (with securities valued at cost) fell to 18.6% from 19.4%. We believe the latter yardstick to be the most appropriate measure of single-year managerial economic performance.</p>
<h2>Textile Operations</h2>
<p>The textile industry remained difficult in 1979. We continued to experience poor results, with the industry plagued by excess capacity and rising costs. Our modernization efforts have not yet produced acceptable returns.</p>
<h2>Insurance Operations</h2>
<p>Our insurance operations continued to perform well. National Indemnity Company maintained its excellent underwriting record. GEICO, under Jack Byrne, made further progress in its turnaround, with underwriting results improving significantly.</p>
<h2>Banking Operations</h2>
<p>Illinois National Bank continued its outstanding performance, earning well over 2% after tax on average deposits. Gene Abegg and Bob Kline have maintained the bank's industry-leading profitability.</p>
<h2>Investments</h2>
<p>Our equity investments performed well in 1979. We continued to concentrate our holdings in a few companies that meet our investment criteria. We focus on the long-term business performance of the companies we own, not short-term market fluctuations.</p>
<p><em>Warren E. Buffett, Chairman</em></p>`,
