<p><em>\u2014 \u2726 \u2014</em></p>
<p>The per-share book value of both our Class A and Class B stock increased by 13.0% in 2010. Over the last 46 years, book value has grown from $19 to $84,487, a rate of 20.1% compounded annually.</p>
<p>Berkshire\u2019s net worth increased by $21.6 billion in 2010. That gain was generated by a diverse group of subsidiaries and investments. Our five \u201cpowerhouse\u201d businesses earned $5.3 billion pre-tax, up from $4.3 billion in 2009.</p>
<p>Our railroad and utility subsidiaries had record earnings. BNSF, which we purchased in early 2009, immediately enhanced Berkshire\u2019s earning power. MidAmerican, which we bought in early 2000, has increased its earnings dramatically.</p>
<p>Our insurance operations continue to be the core of Berkshire. GEICO, which we own outright, ran up record profits. Its market share among U.S. auto insurers grew from 5.7% in 2005 to 7.3% in 2010.</p>
<p>Looking ahead, Charlie and I hope to build Berkshire\u2019s per-share intrinsic value by improving the earnings of our many subsidiaries, making bolt-on acquisitions, and occasionally making large acquisitions.</p>`,
