  {
    slug: '2011-berkshire-letter',
    year: 2011,
    type: 'berkshire',
    title: 'Stable Foundation \u2014 2011',
    date: '2012-02-01',
    summary:
      "2011 was a year of measured progress. Book value rose 4.6%, compounding at 19.8% annually over 47 years. Key developments included hiring Todd Combs and Ted Weschler as investment managers, the $9 billion acquisition of Lubrizol, and record $8.2 billion capital expenditures. Berkshire deployed $5 billion into Bank of America preferred shares and $10.9 billion into IBM. Buffett acknowledged his biggest mistake: the Energy Future Holdings bond purchase, requiring $1 billion in write-downs. Housing remained depressed. Insurance float grew to $70 billion, delivering nine consecutive years of underwriting profit.",
    fullText: `<p>The per-share book value of both our Class A and Class B stock increased by 4.6% in 2011. Over the last 47 years, book value has grown from $19 to $99,860, a rate of 19.8% compounded annually.</p>
<p>Charlie Munger, Berkshire\u2019s Vice Chairman and my partner, and I feel good about the company\u2019s progress during 2011.</p>
<p>The primary job of a Board of Directors is to see that the right people are running the business and to be sure that the next generation of leaders is identified and ready to take over tomorrow. As 2011 started, Todd Combs joined us as an investment manager, and shortly after yearend Ted Weschler came aboard.</p>
<p>On September 16th we acquired Lubrizol, a worldwide producer of additives and other specialty chemicals. The company has had an outstanding record since James Hambrick became CEO in 2004, with pre-tax profits increasing from $147 million to $1,085 million.</p>
<p>Our major businesses did well last year. Each of our five largest non-insurance companies delivered record operating earnings. In aggregate these businesses earned more than $9 billion pre-tax in 2011.</p>
<p>Our insurance operations continued their delivery of costless capital that funds a myriad of other opportunities. We\u2019ve now had nine consecutive years of underwriting profits, totaling about $17 billion. Over the same nine years our float increased from $41 billion to its current record of $70 billion.</p>
<p>We made two major investments in marketable securities: a $5 billion 6% preferred stock of Bank of America and 63.9 million shares of IBM that cost us $10.9 billion. We now have large ownership interests in four exceptional companies: American Express, Coca-Cola, IBM and Wells Fargo.</p>
<p>A few years back, I spent about $2 billion buying several bond issues of Energy Future Holdings. That was a mistake \u2013 a big mistake. We wrote down our investment by $1 billion in 2010 and by an additional $390 million last year. In tennis parlance, this was a major unforced error by your chairman.</p>
<p>Last year, I told you that \u201ca housing recovery will probably begin within a year or so.\u201d I was dead wrong. Housing will come back \u2013 you can be sure of that. America\u2019s best days lie ahead.</p>`,
    concepts: ['intrinsic-value', 'moat', 'compounding', 'succession', 'insurance-float', 'housing'],
    companies: ['berkshire-hathaway'],
    people: ['warren-buffett', 'charlie-munger'],
    crossReferences: [],
